rt of the second halftime in the [[First Macedonian Football League]] match against [[FK Renova|Renova]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/report/1-mfl-2016-abstieg-fk-renova-metalurg-skopje/|title='1 MFL 2016 Abstieg Renova Metalurg Skopje'|website=www.worldfootball.net|language=en|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref> That season he went on to play two more games, which eventually brought him a transfer to [[FK Vardar]] in the following summer in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/todor-todoroski/mkd-1-mfl-2016-abstieg/metalurg-skopje/3/|title='Todor Todoroski: 1 MFL 2016 Abstieg - Metalurg Skopje'|website=www.worldfootball.net|language=en|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref> Vardar initially signed him for their youth team, but in 2017 they eventually promoted him to the first team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/todor-todoroski/mkd-1-mfl-2016-2017/vardar-skopje/3/|title='Todor Todoroski: 1 mfl 2016-2017 - Vardar Skopje'|website=www.worldfootball.net|language=en|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://old.ekipa.mk/todoroski-da-go-nosish-dresot-na-vardar-neprotsenlivo-chuvstvo/|title='\u0422\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0438: \u0414\u0430 \u0433\u043e \u043d\u043e\u0441\u0438\u0448 \u0434\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043e\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0412\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0430\u0440 \u2013 \u043d\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0446\u0435\u043d\u043b\u0438\u0432\u043e \u0447\u0443\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e'|website=www.ekipa.mk|language=mk|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref> Todor was regular in the upcomming [[2017\u201318 Macedonian First Football League|2017\u201318]] and [[2018\u201319 Macedonian First Football League|2018\u201319]] seasons, which cought the eye of Croatian side [[NK Osijek]] who decided to sign him at the beginning of 2019 to play for their second team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nk-osijek.hr/vijesti/18141/nova-lica-u-osjeckim-redovima/|title='Nova lica u Osjeckim redovima'|website=www.nk-osijek.hr|language=hr|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref> After successful 6 months playing for Osijek II in the [[Croatian Second Football League]], in the summer of 2019 they decided to promote him to the first team. On 28 July 2019, he made his debut for the first [[NK Osijek|Osijek]] team, having played the full game against [[NK Gorica|Gorica]] in the second round of the [[2019\u201320 Croatian First Football League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/todor-todoroski/cro-1-hnl-2019-2020/nk-osijek/3/|title='Todor Todoroski: CRO 1 HNL 2019-2020 - NK Osijek'|website=www.worldfootball.net|language=en|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref>\n\n===International career===\nEver since 2014 Todoroski has been regular at most of North Macedonia's national youth teams.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WorldFootball.net|todor-todoroski}}\n* {{Soccerway|todor-todoroski/387441}}\n\n{{NK Osijek squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Todoroski, Todor}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Prilep]]\n[[Category:Macedonian footballers]]\n[[Category:North Macedonia international footballers]]\n[[Category:North Macedonia youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:FK Vardar players]]\n[[Category:NK Osijek players]]\n[[Category:Macedonian First Football League players]]\n\n\n{{RMacedonia-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlaying career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: omming \u2192 oming", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Todor_Todoroski"}
{"title_page": "Richard Blais", "text_new": "{{short description|American chef}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox chef <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox chef/doc]] -->\n| name = Richard Blais\n| image = Richard Blais.jpg\n| caption = Blais in 2011\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = [[Uniondale, New York]], US\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| style = \n| education = [[The Culinary Institute of America]]\n| restaurants = <br />Juniper & Ivy ([[San Diego, California|San Diego]])<br />The Crack Shack (3 locations)\n| television = ''[[Top Chef]]''; ''[[Iron Chef America]]'';''[[Guy's Grocery Games]]''\n| prevrests =\n| awards =\n| website = [http://www.richardblais.net RichardBlais.net]\n}}\n\n'''Richard Blais''' is an American chef, television personality, restaurateur and author. He appeared on the [[reality show]] cooking show ''[[Top Chef]]'',<ref name=\"Dekker\">{{cite web|url=http://www.columbusalive.com/entertainment/20170125/eat--drink-preview-richard-blais-of-top-chef|title=Eat & Drink preview: Richard Blais of 'Top Chef'|last= Dekker|first=Nicholas |date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref> and is known for his take on classic American cuisine. Blais was the runner-up for the fourth season of ''Top Chef'' and returned several seasons later to win ''[[Top Chef (season 8)|Top Chef: All-Stars]]''.\n\n==Education and early career==\n\nBlais was born in [[Uniondale, New York]].{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}} He was adopted by his stepfather in the second grade.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=10}} In 1982 as a pitcher for his \"Franks Pizza\" [[Little League]] team, Richard came in to pitch the final playoff game of the season with his team down by 2 runs. He managed to no hit the mighty \"Sunocco\" team for the next 5 innings as his squad scored 3 runs to win the game.<ref>Ken Blais</ref> Blais' first cooking job was in a [[McDonald's]] on Long Island, where he learned the basics of working in a kitchen.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=10}} Coming from a humble beginnings, Blias dreamed of reinvening himself as a sophisticated Manhatinite. After moving on to a couple upscale restaurants while in college,{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=12}} he received the 2 year [[Associate's degree|AOS]] in [[culinary art]]s from [[The Culinary Institute of America]].{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=12}}  After graduation, he was invited to complete a fellowship in the fish kitchen.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=12}} He has studied under chefs [[Thomas Keller]] at [[The French Laundry]],{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}} [[Daniel Boulud]], and [[Ferran Adri\u00e0]].{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=12}}  He also trained at restaurants [[Chez Panisse]] and [[elBulli]].{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}}\n\n==Career==\n\nA native New Yorker, Blais relocated to Atlanta, Georgia in 2000 to run his own restaurant, called Fishbone.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=13}} Initially, he was unimpressed with traditionally [[Cuisine of the Southern United States|Southern]] ingredients, but found ways to elevate them in his own style.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=13}} He founded Trail Blais, a creative culinary company that has consulted on, designed and operated some of Atlanta's most popular eateries.\n\nIn July 2011, Blais signed a cookbook deal with Clarkson Potter, a division of Random House. On February 26, he released his debut cookbook, ''Try This at Home: Recipes From My Head to Your Plate'', an effort to make a simplified approach to adventurous cooking and offers new flavor combinations for home cooks to reinvent classic dishes.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=13}} ''Try This at Home'' was nominated for a James Beard Foundation Award 2014 in the category of Cookbook: General Cooking. Blais later opened Juniper & Ivy with Michael Rosen in [[San Diego, California]], his first West Coast venture, where he showcases an innovative approach to California cuisine. He and Michael most recently opened Crack Shack, a fried chicken fine-casual concept, where the menu is built around chicken and eggs.<ref name=\"Dekker\"/> Crack Shack has multiple locations in San Diego, Encinitas, Orange County and soon,{{when|date=June 2017}} Los Angeles.\n\nOn May 16, 2017, Blais released his second cookbook, ''So Good: 100 Recipes from My Kitchen to Yours'', which features 100 elevated traditional recipes designed for the home cook.\n\nAlso in 2017, Blais began hosting a weekly [[podcast]] about the culinary industry called ''Starving For Attention''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/166943/podcastone-adds-starving-for-attention-with-richar | title=Podcast One Adds 'Starving For Attention With Richard Blais' |publisher=All Access | access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Blais and [[iHeartRadio]] launched the game-show-style podcast [https://megaphone.link/foodcourt \"Food Court with Richard Blais\"] which features guests including celebrity chefs, actors, writers, comedians and other podcasters debating classic food arguments. \n\n===''Top Chef ''===\n\n[[File:Richard Blais.JPG|thumb|right|Richard Blais]]\n\nBlais appeared as a contestant on the 4th season of [[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]]'s ''[[Top Chef (season 4)|Top Chef]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bravotv.com/Top_Chef/season/4/bios/index.php?cat=chef&p=richard|title=Season 4 Bios: Richard Blais|author=Bravotv.com|accessdate=June 1, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124234658/http://www.bravotv.com/Top_Chef/season/4/bios/index.php?cat=chef&p=richard|archivedate=January 24, 2009}}</ref> In 2010, he competed in ''[[Top Chef (season 8)|Top Chef: All-Stars]]'' and won the competition, earning the title of \"Top Chef\" by defeating Mike Isabella in the season finale, which aired on March 30, 2011. He was a recurring judge in seasons 12 and 13.\n\n===Other television appearances===\n\nBlais is a regular on the [[Food Network]], with recurring appearances on ''[[Guy's Grocery Games]]'' as a judge,{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}} and as a competitor, and has also hosted Food Network's ''Hungry Games'', and ''[[Halloween Baking Championship]]''. He competed in the second ''[[Cutthroat Kitchen#Superstar Sabotage Tournament|Cutthroat Kitchen: Superstar Sabotage]]'' tournament on November 4, 2015, winning his preliminary match and advancing to the finals; he had been a recurring judge on that series since season 12. He also has a recurring role as judge in the ''[[Masterchef]]'' and ''[[Masterchef Junior]]'' franchise.  In 2015, Blais was the host of HLN's \"Cook Your Ass Off,\"{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}} a transformational culinary contest that focused on healthy cooking competition. In 2017 he became the host of \"Man v. Master,\"<ref name=\"Dekker\"/>{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}} a culinary competition on the FYI Network. Richard has also appeared on various talk shows, including ''[[The TODAY Show]]'', ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[The Rachael Ray Show]]'', ''[[The Chew]]'', ''[[Live! with Kelly and Michael]]'', and ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]''. Blais had a cameo role in the 2016 feature film, ''[[Why Him?]]'', starring [[James Franco]] and [[Bryan Cranston]].<ref name=\"Dekker\"/> In 2018, Blais appeared as a guest judge on [[Sugar Rush (2018 TV series)|''Sugar Rush'']].<ref>{{Citation|title=Sugar Rush - Season 1, Episode 4|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sugar_rush/s01/e04|language=en|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref>\n\n===Restaurants===\n\nBlais is currently or has been involved with:\n\n*Juniper & Ivy \u2013 An American restaurant that opened in [[San Diego, California|San Diego]] in March 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sandiego.eater.com/archives/2014/03/03/eater-takes-you-inside-juniper-ivy-plus-a-menu-reveal.php |title=Inside Most Anticipated Juniper & Ivy, Plus a Menu Reveal| author = Eater.com |accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref> At Juniper & Ivy, Blais offers refined, American cuisine with a \"left coast edge.\"\n\n*The Crack Shack \u2013 Blais partnered with chef Jon Sloan and Michael Rosen on this second San Diego-based restaurant, which opened in late 2015. The restaurant, \"serves breakfast, lunch and dinner via an all-day menu that revolves around chicken and eggs, from fried to grilled and everything in-between\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Richard Blais Jumps into Chicken (and Egg) Game With Crack Shack|url = http://sandiego.eater.com/2015/3/24/8283527/richard-blais-new-juniper-ivy-team-restaurant-crack-shack|website = Eater San Diego|access-date = 2016-02-02}}</ref> Crack Shack plans to expand to multiple locations throughout California including Orange County and Los Angeles.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} \n\n*[[FLIP Burger Boutique]] \u2013 Blais was formerly involved with and co-founder of burger-focused restaurant, FLIP Burger Boutique, with three locations in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], one in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] (closed), and a location in Nashville, Tennessee (closed).<ref>{{cite web|title=FLIP Burger|url=http://www.flipburgerboutique.com|website=Flip Burger Boutique|accessdate=11 August 2011|language=en}}</ref>. Blais is no longer involved with the FLIP chain.\n\n==Other activities==\n\nIn November 2011, Blais ran the ING New York City marathon for Alliance for a Healthier Generation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnston|first1=Lauren|title=2011 NYC marathon celebrity runners announced! And the runners are ...|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/running-dialogue/2011-nyc-marathon-celebrity-runners-announced-runners-blog-entry-1.1625214|accessdate=2 July 2016|agency=Running Dialogue|publisher=NYDailyNews.com|date=29 September 2011}}</ref> It was his first marathon, and he completed it in 4:31:54.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Murphy|first1=Jen|title=In Pursuit of Love, Chef Learns to Love Running|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324048904578320691720454324|accessdate=2 July 2016|agency=The Wall Street Journal|publisher=Dow Jones & Company, Inc.|date=25 February 2013}}</ref> He has since run four other New York City marathons. In November 2017, Blais ran the TCS New York City Marathon for Room to Read.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20171030005261/en/Richard-Blais-Active-Education-Room-Read-TCS|title=Richard Blais Gets Active for Education with Room to Read at TCS New York City Marathon|website=Businesswire.com|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n\n*{{cite book| ref=harv |last1= Blais |first1=Richard |first2=Tom |last2=Colicchio|title=Try This at Home: Recipes from My Head to Your Plate|publisher= Potter/TenSpeed/Harmony|date=2013 |isbn=0307985288}}\n*{{cite book| ref=harv |last=Blais |first=Richard |title=So Good: 100 Recipes from My Kitchen to Yours|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|date=2017 |isbn=0544663098}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*{{Official website|http://www.richardblais.net}}\n* [http://www.bravotv.com/top-chef/bio/richard-blais Bravo TV biography]\n\n{{Top Chef}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blais, Richard}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Male chefs]]\n[[Category:American chefs]]\n[[Category:People from Uniondale, New York]]\n[[Category:Writers from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Top Chef winners]]\n[[Category:Top Chef contestants]]\n[[Category:Restaurant groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Culinary Institute of America alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American chef}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox chef <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox chef/doc]] -->\n| name = Richard Blais\n| image = Richard Blais.jpg\n| caption = Blais in 2011\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = [[Uniondale, New York]], US\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| style = \n| education = [[The Culinary Institute of America]]\n| restaurants = <br />Juniper & Ivy ([[San Diego, California|San Diego]])<br />The Crack Shack (3 locations)\n| television = ''[[Top Chef]]''; ''[[Iron Chef America]]'';''[[Guy's Grocery Games]]''\n| prevrests =\n| awards =\n| website = [http://www.richardblais.net RichardBlais.net]\n}}\n\n'''Richard Blais''' is an American chef, television personality, restaurateur and author. He appeared on the [[reality show]] cooking show ''[[Top Chef]]'',<ref name=\"Dekker\">{{cite web|url=http://www.columbusalive.com/entertainment/20170125/eat--drink-preview-richard-blais-of-top-chef|title=Eat & Drink preview: Richard Blais of 'Top Chef'|last= Dekker|first=Nicholas |date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref> and is known for his take on classic American cuisine. Blais was the runner-up for the fourth season of ''Top Chef'' and returned several seasons later to win ''[[Top Chef (season 8)|Top Chef: All-Stars]]''.\n\n==Education and early career==\n\nBlais was born in [[Uniondale, New York]].{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}} He was adopted by his stepfather in the second grade.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=10}} In 1982 as a pitcher for his \"Franks Pizza\" [[Little League]] team, Richard came in to pitch the final playoff game of the season with his team down by 2 runs. He managed to no hit the mighty \"Sunocco\" team for the next 5 innings as his squad scored 3 runs to win the game.<ref>Ken Blais</ref> Blais' first cooking job was in a [[McDonald's]] on Long Island, where he learned the basics of working in a kitchen.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=10}} Comming from a humble beginings, Blias dreamed of reinvening himself as a sophisticated Manhatinite. After moving on to a couple upscale restaurants while in college,{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=12}} he received the 2 year [[Associate's degree|AOS]] in [[culinary art]]s from [[The Culinary Institute of America]].{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=12}}  After graduation, he was invited to complete a fellowship in the fish kitchen.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=12}} He has studied under chefs [[Thomas Keller]] at [[The French Laundry]],{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}} [[Daniel Boulud]], and [[Ferran Adri\u00e0]].{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=12}}  He also trained at restaurants [[Chez Panisse]] and [[elBulli]].{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}}\n\n==Career==\n\nA native New Yorker, Blais relocated to Atlanta, Georgia in 2000 to run his own restaurant, called Fishbone.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=13}} Initially, he was unimpressed with traditionally [[Cuisine of the Southern United States|Southern]] ingredients, but found ways to elevate them in his own style.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=13}} He founded Trail Blais, a creative culinary company that has consulted on, designed and operated some of Atlanta's most popular eateries.\n\nIn July 2011, Blais signed a cookbook deal with Clarkson Potter, a division of Random House. On February 26, he released his debut cookbook, ''Try This at Home: Recipes From My Head to Your Plate'', an effort to make a simplified approach to adventurous cooking and offers new flavor combinations for home cooks to reinvent classic dishes.{{sfn|Blais|Colicchio|2013|p=13}} ''Try This at Home'' was nominated for a James Beard Foundation Award 2014 in the category of Cookbook: General Cooking. Blais later opened Juniper & Ivy with Michael Rosen in [[San Diego, California]], his first West Coast venture, where he showcases an innovative approach to California cuisine. He and Michael most recently opened Crack Shack, a fried chicken fine-casual concept, where the menu is built around chicken and eggs.<ref name=\"Dekker\"/> Crack Shack has multiple locations in San Diego, Encinitas, Orange County and soon,{{when|date=June 2017}} Los Angeles.\n\nOn May 16, 2017, Blais released his second cookbook, ''So Good: 100 Recipes from My Kitchen to Yours'', which features 100 elevated traditional recipes designed for the home cook.\n\nAlso in 2017, Blais began hosting a weekly [[podcast]] about the culinary industry called ''Starving For Attention''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/166943/podcastone-adds-starving-for-attention-with-richar | title=Podcast One Adds 'Starving For Attention With Richard Blais' |publisher=All Access | access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Blais and [[iHeartRadio]] launched the game-show-style podcast [https://megaphone.link/foodcourt \"Food Court with Richard Blais\"] which features guests including celebrity chefs, actors, writers, comedians and other podcasters debating classic food arguments. \n\n===''Top Chef ''===\n\n[[File:Richard Blais.JPG|thumb|right|Richard Blais]]\n\nBlais appeared as a contestant on the 4th season of [[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]]'s ''[[Top Chef (season 4)|Top Chef]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bravotv.com/Top_Chef/season/4/bios/index.php?cat=chef&p=richard|title=Season 4 Bios: Richard Blais|author=Bravotv.com|accessdate=June 1, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124234658/http://www.bravotv.com/Top_Chef/season/4/bios/index.php?cat=chef&p=richard|archivedate=January 24, 2009}}</ref> In 2010, he competed in ''[[Top Chef (season 8)|Top Chef: All-Stars]]'' and won the competition, earning the title of \"Top Chef\" by defeating Mike Isabella in the season finale, which aired on March 30, 2011. He was a recurring judge in seasons 12 and 13.\n\n===Other television appearances===\n\nBlais is a regular on the [[Food Network]], with recurring appearances on ''[[Guy's Grocery Games]]'' as a judge,{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}} and as a competitor, and has also hosted Food Network's ''Hungry Games'', and ''[[Halloween Baking Championship]]''. He competed in the second ''[[Cutthroat Kitchen#Superstar Sabotage Tournament|Cutthroat Kitchen: Superstar Sabotage]]'' tournament on November 4, 2015, winning his preliminary match and advancing to the finals; he had been a recurring judge on that series since season 12. He also has a recurring role as judge in the ''[[Masterchef]]'' and ''[[Masterchef Junior]]'' franchise.  In 2015, Blais was the host of HLN's \"Cook Your Ass Off,\"{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}} a transformational culinary contest that focused on healthy cooking competition. In 2017 he became the host of \"Man v. Master,\"<ref name=\"Dekker\"/>{{sfn|Blais|2017|p=13}} a culinary competition on the FYI Network. Richard has also appeared on various talk shows, including ''[[The TODAY Show]]'', ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[The Rachael Ray Show]]'', ''[[The Chew]]'', ''[[Live! with Kelly and Michael]]'', and ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]''. Blais had a cameo role in the 2016 feature film, ''[[Why Him?]]'', starring [[James Franco]] and [[Bryan Cranston]].<ref name=\"Dekker\"/> In 2018, Blais appeared as a guest judge on [[Sugar Rush (2018 TV series)|''Sugar Rush'']].<ref>{{Citation|title=Sugar Rush - Season 1, Episode 4|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/sugar_rush/s01/e04|language=en|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref>\n\n===Restaurants===\n\nBlais is currently or has been involved with:\n\n*Juniper & Ivy \u2013 An American restaurant that opened in [[San Diego, California|San Diego]] in March 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sandiego.eater.com/archives/2014/03/03/eater-takes-you-inside-juniper-ivy-plus-a-menu-reveal.php |title=Inside Most Anticipated Juniper & Ivy, Plus a Menu Reveal| author = Eater.com |accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref> At Juniper & Ivy, Blais offers refined, American cuisine with a \"left coast edge.\"\n\n*The Crack Shack \u2013 Blais partnered with chef Jon Sloan and Michael Rosen on this second San Diego-based restaurant, which opened in late 2015. The restaurant, \"serves breakfast, lunch and dinner via an all-day menu that revolves around chicken and eggs, from fried to grilled and everything in-between\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Richard Blais Jumps into Chicken (and Egg) Game With Crack Shack|url = http://sandiego.eater.com/2015/3/24/8283527/richard-blais-new-juniper-ivy-team-restaurant-crack-shack|website = Eater San Diego|access-date = 2016-02-02}}</ref> Crack Shack plans to expand to multiple locations throughout California including Orange County and Los Angeles.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} \n\n*[[FLIP Burger Boutique]] \u2013 Blais was formerly involved with and co-founder of burger-focused restaurant, FLIP Burger Boutique, with three locations in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], one in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] (closed), and a location in Nashville, Tennessee (closed).<ref>{{cite web|title=FLIP Burger|url=http://www.flipburgerboutique.com|website=Flip Burger Boutique|accessdate=11 August 2011|language=en}}</ref>. Blais is no longer involved with the FLIP chain.\n\n==Other activities==\n\nIn November 2011, Blais ran the ING New York City marathon for Alliance for a Healthier Generation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnston|first1=Lauren|title=2011 NYC marathon celebrity runners announced! And the runners are ...|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/running-dialogue/2011-nyc-marathon-celebrity-runners-announced-runners-blog-entry-1.1625214|accessdate=2 July 2016|agency=Running Dialogue|publisher=NYDailyNews.com|date=29 September 2011}}</ref> It was his first marathon, and he completed it in 4:31:54.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Murphy|first1=Jen|title=In Pursuit of Love, Chef Learns to Love Running|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324048904578320691720454324|accessdate=2 July 2016|agency=The Wall Street Journal|publisher=Dow Jones & Company, Inc.|date=25 February 2013}}</ref> He has since run four other New York City marathons. In November 2017, Blais ran the TCS New York City Marathon for Room to Read.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20171030005261/en/Richard-Blais-Active-Education-Room-Read-TCS|title=Richard Blais Gets Active for Education with Room to Read at TCS New York City Marathon|website=Businesswire.com|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n\n*{{cite book| ref=harv |last1= Blais |first1=Richard |first2=Tom |last2=Colicchio|title=Try This at Home: Recipes from My Head to Your Plate|publisher= Potter/TenSpeed/Harmony|date=2013 |isbn=0307985288}}\n*{{cite book| ref=harv |last=Blais |first=Richard |title=So Good: 100 Recipes from My Kitchen to Yours|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|date=2017 |isbn=0544663098}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*{{Official website|http://www.richardblais.net}}\n* [http://www.bravotv.com/top-chef/bio/richard-blais Bravo TV biography]\n\n{{Top Chef}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blais, Richard}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Male chefs]]\n[[Category:American chefs]]\n[[Category:People from Uniondale, New York]]\n[[Category:Writers from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Top Chef winners]]\n[[Category:Top Chef contestants]]\n[[Category:Restaurant groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Culinary Institute of America alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation and early career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: beginings \u2192 beginnings, omming \u2192 oming", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Blais"}
{"title_page": "Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show", "text_new": "{{short description|Annual conformation show in New York City}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2007}}\n[[File:StumpWestminsterShow-wiki.jpg|thumb|Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show]]\nThe '''Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show''' is an all-breed [[conformation show]] that has been hosted in [[New York City]] annually since 1877. Currently, the breed and Junior Showmanship competitions are hosted at Piers 92 and 94, while the group and Best in Show competitions take place at [[Madison Square Garden]].\n\nThe Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show is one of a handful of [[Bench show|benched shows]] in the United States. Dogs are required to be on display in their assigned locations (show benches) during the entire show except when shown in the ring, groomed for showtime, or taken outside for elimination. This type of presentation allows spectators and breeders alike to have an opportunity of seeing all the entered dogs. (In the more common unbenched shows, dogs are required to be present only at assigned ring times.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.akc.org/expert-advice/sports/allan-unleashed-engaging-positively-public/|title=Engaging Positively With the Public at Dog Shows|first=Allan|last=Reznik|website=American Kennel Club|date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:WKC Dog Show Logo 2019.png|alt=A black-and-white stylized drawing of a hunting dog, nose poked out to the left of the image, tail erect and behind the dog, with a group of trees in the background.|thumb|The [[Westminster Kennel Club]] was formed in 1877.]]\nThe first Westminster show took place on May 8, 1877, making it second only to the [[Kentucky Derby]], in terms of continuously held sporting events in the United States. (Both events were held despite the [[Great Depression]] & [[World War]] years.) The show originated as a show for [[gun dog]]s, primarily [[Setter]]s and [[pointer (dog)|Pointers]], initiated by a group of hunters who met regularly at the Westminster Hotel at Irving Place and Sixteenth Street in [[Manhattan]]. They decided to create a [[kennel club]] called the Westminster Kennel Club specifically to hold a dog show. The prizes for these first shows included such items as pearl-handled pistols, which were of use to the hunters and terriermen who worked these dogs in the field.\n\n[[File:(King1893NYC) pg240 WESTMINISTER HOTEL, IRVING PLACE AND 16TH STREET.jpg|thumb|left|WESTMINISTER HOTEL, IRVING PLACE AND 16TH STREET]]\nHeld at Gilmore's Garden ([[Madison Square Garden (1879)|Madison Square Garden]]) the Westminster show drew over 1200 dogs. It proved so popular that it took four days instead of the three days originally scheduled. The club donated proceeds from the fourth day to the [[ASPCA]] for creation of a home for stray and disabled dogs.\n\nThe Westminster Kennel Club predates the formation of the [[American Kennel Club]] by seven years and became the first club admitted to the AKC after AKC's founding in 1884.  Breed parent clubs (e.g., the Collie  Club of America) create the standards for judging their breeds, with the AKC administering the rules about shows and judging.\n\nDogs are judged by how closely they conform to a written description of the ideal specimen of that breed (the breed standard). Many breeds no longer need to perform their original jobs and are bred mostly for companionship. However, they are still judged on their innate ability and physical makeup to perform their original jobs. Standards also include items that seem somewhat arbitrary such as color, eye shape, tail carriage and more.\n\nToday, Westminster takes place over two days and nights every February.  During the day, the dogs compete against other dogs of the same breed at Piers 92 and 94. Each Best of Breed winner (BOB) advances to the Group level. There are seven groups: Sporting, Hound, Working, Terrier, Toy, Non-Sporting, and Herding.  Group competition occurs during the evenings at Madison Square Garden. The seven Group winners advance to Best in Show, the final round of the show. During Best in Show, also held at Madison Square Garden, a judge will select one of judging othem as the Best In Show winner. Since 2014, the show allowed mixed-breed dogs to compete in an agility event.<ref>Jennifer Peltz, \"[https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/westminster-dog-show-adds-event-mixed-breeds-21547820 Westminster Dog Show Adds Event With Mixed Breeds],\" Associated Press, January 16, 2014.</ref>\n\nWestminster has held competitions in Junior Showmanship for handlers ages 9\u201318 since 1934. The eight finalists all receive scholarships for post-secondary schooling. The Club, through the Westminster Kennel Foundation also awards veterinary school scholarships for students from six schools yearly.\n\nThe winning dog becomes \"America's Dog\" for the coming year. Their reign begins with a media tour on the day following the show. They make appearances on nearly all television network morning shows, visit to the Observation Deck at the Empire State Building. The New York Stock Exchange also invites the winner to ring the opening bell.\n\nThe event is widely celebrated in New York City every February. The Empire State Building salutes the show by lighting its tower in the Westminster colors of purple and gold for the duration of the show. Saks 5th Avenue features a street window with a Westminster-themed display.\n\n==Controversy==\nAnimal-rights advocates such as [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] protest the show, arguing that the propagation and celebration of purebreds ultimately add to the millions of dogs who end up at and die in shelters.<ref>Jennifer Peltz, \"[https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/westminster-dog-show-adds-event-mixed-breeds-21547820 Westminster Dog Show Adds Event With Mixed Breeds,\"] Associated Press, 16 January 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.humanesociety.org/issues/pet_overpopulation/facts/pet_ownership_statistics.html Pets By the Numbers],\" Humane Society of the United States, September 27, 2013.</ref>\n\nAlso, during the 2019 broadcast, [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]] was reprimanded by dog show sponsor [[Ralston Purina|Purina]] after a broadcast voice-over introduction of a dog breed was done by [[NASCAR Cup Series]] champion [[Kyle Busch]], who is sponsored by a rival pet food maker, [[Mars Petcare]].\n\n==Announcers==\nFor many years, [[Roger A. Caras]] was known as \"the Voice of Westminster\" for providing the narration for the breed descriptions during the show.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/20/nyregion/roger-caras-72-animal-welfare-advocate.html | work=The New York Times | first=Sherri | last=Day | title=Roger Caras, 72, Animal Welfare Advocate | date=February 20, 2001}}</ref><ref>http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2012/02/11/v-print/2226292/pets-qa-best-in-show-really-means.html</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Michael J. LaFave was named show announcer at the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show.<ref>{{cite web|title=2004 Announcer|url=http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/2004/show/lafave.html|work=The Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show|publisher=Westminster Kennel Club|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref> He was replaced by Jim Fagan in 2010 but returned in 2011.<ref name=Ullmer>{{cite news|last=Ullmer|first=Mary|title=Unleashed: Unleash the hounds! Gentle giant Scottish deerhound is Westminster's Best in Show|url=http://www.mlive.com/living/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2011/02/unleashed_unleash_the_hounds_g.html|accessdate=May 24, 2012|newspaper=The Grand Rapids Press|date=February 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n[[CBS Sports]] covered the event from the late 1960s to the 1980s as part of its ''[[CBS Sports Spectacular]]'' anthology series.\n\nFrom 1984 until 2003, Universal's [[USA Network]] broadcast the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show. Following Universal's acquisition by General Electric in 2003 to form [[NBC Universal]], from 2004 until 2016, the show aired under the [[NBC Sports]] label. From 2006 through 2016, the Monday coverage was aired by business news channel [[CNBC]] due to conflicts with ''[[WWE Raw]]'' on the USA Network. On July 28, 2015, [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]] announced that it had acquired rights to the event under a 10-year deal beginning in 2017. For the first three years, [[Fox Sports 1]] and [[Nat Geo Wild]] provided joint coverage the show.\n\nDuring NBC's coverage from 1990 to 2016, [[David Frei]] co-hosted the event with partners, [[Al Trautwig]] (1990\u20131991,<ref>{{cite news|last=Dawson|first=Greg|title=USA's Westminster Dog Show a cult hit|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EYpJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DAwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5111,336923&dq|accessdate=May 24, 2012|newspaper=The News and Courier|date=February 16, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Zad|first=Martie|title=TNT features 'Kisses'|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-XlGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TOkMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3663,2494169&dq|accessdate=May 24, 2012|newspaper=The Daily Gazette|date=February 10, 1991}}</ref> 1993<ref>{{cite news|title=The dog days of February|newspaper=The Washington Times|date=February 13, 1993}}</ref>), [[Bud Collins]] (1992<ref>{{cite news|title=Bud Collins to Test Commentator Skills at National Dog Show|newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader|date=February 10, 1992}}</ref>), [[Joe Garagiola]] (1994\u20132002<ref>{{cite news|last=Dale|first=Steve|title=Canine Frenzy|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TvtPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ywgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6816,6119383&dq|accessdate=May 25, 2012|newspaper=Ocala Star-Banner|date=February 10, 2002}}</ref>), [[Mark McEwen]] (2003\u20132004<ref>{{cite web|last=Dale|first=Steve|title=The Voice of Westminster Dog Show|url=http://www.dogchannel.com/show/article_18009.aspx|work=Dog Channel.com|publisher=BowTie, Inc.|accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pennington|first=Gail|title=Critic's Picks|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=February 9, 2004}}</ref>), [[Lester Holt]] (2005, 2007\u20132008<ref>{{cite news|title=Westminster puts on the dogs|newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader|date=February 7, 2008}}</ref>), [[Debbye Turner]] (2006<ref>{{cite news|title=TV Digest|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=January 23, 2006}}</ref>), [[Mary Carillo]] (2009,<ref>{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=Former Westminster Winners Do Not Seem Past Their Prime|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/09/sports/othersports/09dogs.html|accessdate=May 25, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 8, 2009}}</ref> 2011<ref name=Ullmer />\u20132016), and [[Tamron Hall]] (2010<ref>{{cite web|title=USA Network & Westminster Brings Everyone's Best Friend Back to Madison Square Garden|url=http://newsblaze.com/story/2010012911590200001.pnw/topstory.html|work=News Blaze|accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref>).\n\nFrei provided the commentary of the 140th event for his final time. \n\nThe 141st event in 2017 marked the beginning of the [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]] contract. There are two sets of hosting teams.  From 2017\u201319, coverage aired on [[Fox Sports 1]] and [[National Geographic Wild]].  For 2017, daytime breed judging was hosted by [[Justin Kutcher]], Paula Nykiel and Jason Hoke and primetime coverage hosted by [[Chris Myers]] and Gail Miller Bisher.  In 2018, daytime bred judging was hosted by Kutcher, Kimberly Meredith Cavanna and Don Sturz in 2018, while Hoke joined the evening booth of Myers and Bisher. In 2019, the judging experts were swapped, with the day event hosted by Kutcher, Cavanna, and Hoke and evening event by Myers, Bisher, and Sturz.  <ref>{{cite web|title=Fox Sports Names Pick of the Litter for the 2017 Westminister Dog Show|url=http://www.foxsports.com/presspass/latestnews/2017/01/12/fox-sports-names-pick-of-the-litter-for-2017-westminster-dog-sho|website=Fox Sports Press Pass|publisher=Fox Sports public relations|date=January 12, 2017}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the acquisition of National Geographic TV Channels and the Fox TV Studios by the Walt Disney Company in 2019, event coverage in 2020 is limited solely to the two Fox Sports channels, Fox Sports 1 for primetime and [[Fox Sports 2]] for daytime judging.  [[John Strong (sportscaster)|John Strong]] replaced Kutcher as host for daytime breed judging and Fox hosts were Myers, Bisher, and Sturz.\n\nIn 2017, Fox Sports 1 aired a one-hour documentary, ''Crowned: Inside the Westminster Dog Show.''\n\n== Requirements for entry ==\n\nIn 1884, the AKC began requiring that all dog participants be registered with the AKC and recognized for conformation show competition. In 2016, there are 199 breeds and varieties eligible for Westminster. \nBecause of the show's popularity and prestige, starting in 1992 the AKC limited entries by requiring that dogs must have already earned their breed championship before appearing at Westminster. Later, the AKC amended that rule - dogs only need one of the two required \"major wins\" towards their championship titles. However, they don't need to be finished champions to enter.\n\nThe top five dogs in each breed (based on breed points earned in AKC conformation showing through October 31 of the preceding year), as well as the Best of Breed winner from each breed's national specialty show, receive printed invitations by mail and are eligible for early entry. After that entry deadline passes, other dogs with at least one \"major win\" may enter, up to a cut-off entry total of 2800 dogs.\n\nThere is no prohibition against a winner competing again in future Westminster shows. Seven dogs have won multiple Westminster championships: six dogs in consecutive years (including [[Warren Remedy]], the only three-time champion of the event) and one dog in non-consecutive years. Since 1972, however, there have been no repeat winners. (See [[List of Best in Show winners of the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show]].)\n\nDogs of all breeds, including [[mongrel|mutts]], may participate in the show's agility competition. There is a title for the highest-ranking mutt in the agility round - the \"All American Dog.\"\n\n== Winning breeds ==\n\nThrough the 134th Westminster Show (February 2010), [[Conformation show#Winning|Best in Show]] has been won by the [[Terrier]] group 45 out of the 103 times that the prize has been awarded since 1907,<ref>[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/bisrecords.html WestminsterKennelClub.org - ''Best In Show Awards By Breed (1907-2010)'']</ref> more than twice as many wins as any other group.  The single breed that has won the most is the Wire Fox Terrier, which has won 14 times. Two of the most popular dog breeds in the United States have never won Best in Show - they are the [[Labrador Retriever]] and the [[Golden Retriever]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akc.org/reg/dogreg_stats.cfm|title=The Labrador Retriever Wins Top Breed for the 26th Year In a Row|work=akc.org}}</ref>\n\n* [[Terrier]] group:  46\n* [[Gun dog|Sporting]] group: 18\n* [[Working dog|Working]] group: 15\n* [[Toy dog|Toy]] group: 11\n* Non-Sporting group: 10\n* [[Hound]] group: 6\n* [[Herding dog|Herding]] group: 3\n\nThe oldest dog to win Best in Show was a [[Sussex Spaniel]] named ''Ch. [[Clussexx Three D Grinchy Glee]]'' (a.k.a. Stump), at ten years of age in 2009. The youngest dog to win was a [[Rough Collie]] named ''Laund Loyalty of Bellhaven'', at nine months old in 1929.<ref>[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/bisrecords.html WestminsterKennelClub.org - ''Oldest Dogs To Win Best In Show'']</ref>  One dog, a [[Smooth Fox Terrier]] named ''Ch. Warren Remedy'' won Best in Show three times (1907\u20131909), and six other dogs have won twice.<ref>[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/bisrecords.html  WestminsterKennelClub.org - ''Multiple Best In Show Wins'']</ref>  Males have won Best in Show 68 times as opposed to females who have won 35 times.<ref>[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/bisrecords.html WestminsterKennelClub.org - ''Best In Show Awards By Sex Of The Dog'']</ref>\n\n===List of show winners and breeds===\n{{main|List of Best in Show winners of the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show}}\n\nFollowing is a list of ''WKC Best in Show'' winners since 1990.<ref>[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/biswinners.html Westminsterkennelclub.org - ''Best In Show Winners'']</ref>\n*2020: GCHP Stone Run Afternoon Tea - [[Poodle]]\n*2019: GCHB CH Kingarthur Van Foliny Home - [[Wire Fox Terrier]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/today/2019/02/king-a-wire-fox-terrier-crowned-best-in-show-at-the-2019-westminster-kennel-club-dog-show.html|title=King, a wire fox terrier, crowned best in show at the 2019 Westminster Kennel Club dog show|first1=Amy|last1=Kuperinsky||date=February 13, 2019|work=The Oregonian}}</ref>\n*2018: GCH Belle Creek's All I Care About Is Love - [[Bichon Frise]]\n*2017: Lockenhaus' Rumor Has It V Kenlyn - [[German Shepherd]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/14/sports/winner-westminster-dog-show-best-in-show.html|title=Westminster Dog Show 2017: Rumor the German Shepherd Wins Best in Show|first1=Kelly|last1=Whiteside|first2=Andrew|last2=Das|first3=Sarah|last3=Lyall|date=February 14, 2017|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n*2016: GCH Vjk-Myst Garbonita's California Journey (aka: ''\"CJ\"'') - [[Pointer (German Shorthaired)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2016/02/17/winning_dog_annoying_name.php|title=CJ The German Shorthaired Pointer Named 2016 Best In Show At Westminster Kennel Club's Big Night|last=Chung|first=Jen|website=Gothamist|access-date=October 11, 2016}}</ref>\n*2015: GCH ''[[Tashtins Lookin For Trouble]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Miss P\"'') - [[Beagle]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dogworld.co.uk/product.php/131233/1/canadians_triumph_at_westminster |title=Canadians triumph at Westminster |publisher=[[Dog World (newspaper)|Dog World]] |accessdate=February 18, 2015}}</ref>\n*2014: GCH ''Afterall Painting The Sky'' (a.k.a. ''\"Sky\"'') - [[Wire Fox Terrier]]<ref>http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/2014/results/bis/index.html</ref>\n*2013: GCH ''[[Banana Joe V Tani Kazari]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Banana Joe\"'') - [[Affenpinscher]]\n*2012: Ch. [[Palacegarden Malachy]] (a.k.a. ''\"Malachy\"'') - [[Pekingese]]\n*2011:  GCH ''[[Foxcliffe Hickory Wind]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Hickory\"'') - [[Scottish Deerhound]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://yourlife.usatoday.com/pets/pawprintpost/post/2011/02/westminster-best-in-show-winner/143180/1|title=Westminster Best in Show Winner: Scottish Deerhound|date=February 15, 2011|publisher=usatoday.com | accessdate=February 15, 2011| location=New York }}</ref>\n*2010:  Ch. ''[[Roundtown Mercedes of Maryscot]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Sadie\"'') - [[Scottish Terrier]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/house-and-home/sadie-crowned-top-dog-despite-interruption-1902148.html|title=Sadie crowned top dog despite interruption|date=February 17, 2010|work=The Independent|accessdate=February 17, 2010 | location=London | first=Oliver | last=Duff}}</ref>\n*2009:  Ch. ''[[Clussexx Three D Grinchy Glee]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Stump\"'') - [[Sussex Spaniel]]\n*2008:  Ch. ''[[K-Run's Park Me In First]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Uno''\" ) - [[Beagle]]\n*2007:  Ch. ''[[Felicity's Diamond Jim]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"James\"'' ) - [[English Springer Spaniel]]\n*2006:  Ch. ''Rocky Top's Sundance Kid'' (a.k.a. ''\"Rufus\"'' ) - [[Bull Terrier|Colored Bull Terrier]]\n*2005:  Ch. ''Kan-Point's VJK Autumn Roses'' (a.k.a. ''\"Carlee\"'' ) - [[German Shorthaired Pointer]]\n*2004:  Ch. ''Darbydale's All Rise Pouch Cove'' (a.k.a. ''\"Josh\"'' ) - [[Newfoundland (dog)|Newfoundland]]\n*2003:  Ch. ''[[Torums Scarf Michael]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Mick\"'' ) - [[Kerry Blue Terrier]]\n*2002:  Ch. ''Surrey Spice Girl'' (a.k.a. ''\"Spice\"'' ) - [[Miniature Poodle]]\n*2001:  Ch. ''Special Times Just Right'' (a.k.a. ''\"J.R.\"'' ) - [[Bichon Frise]]\n*2000:  Ch. ''Salilyn 'N Erin's Shameless'' (a.k.a. ''\"Samantha\"'' ) - [[English Springer Spaniel]]\n*1999:  Ch. ''[[Loteki Supernatural Being]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Kirby\"'' ) - [[Papillon (dog)|Papillon]]\n*1998:  Ch. ''Fairewood Frolic'' (a.k.a. ''\"Rocki\"'' ) - [[Norwich Terrier]]\n*1997:  Ch. ''Parsifal Di Casa Netzer'' - [[Standard Schnauzer]]\n*1996:  Ch. ''Clussexx Country Sunrise'' (a.k.a. ''\"Brady\"'' ) - [[Clumber Spaniel]]\n*1995:  Ch. ''Gaelforce Post Script'' (a.k.a. ''\"Peggy Sue\"'' ) - Scottish Terrier\n*1994:  Ch. ''Chidley Willum The Conqueror'' - [[Norwich Terrier]]\n*1993:  Ch. ''Salilyn's Condor'' (a.k.a.: '\"Robert\"'' ) - [[English Springer Spaniel]]\n*1992:  Ch. ''Registry's Lonesome Dove'' (a.k.a. ''\"Lacey\"'' ) - [[Wire Fox Terrier]]\n*1991:  Ch. ''Whisperwind On A Carousel'' (a.k.a. ''\"Peter\"'' ) - [[Standard Poodle]]\n*1990:  Ch. ''Wendessa Crown Prince'' - [[Pekingese]]\n\n==Popular culture==\n* The 2000 comedy film ''[[Best in Show (film)|Best in Show]]'' takes place at the fictional \"Mayflower Kennel Club Dog Show,\" based in part on Westminster.\n*[[Triumph, the Insult Comic Dog]] has used the setting of the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show three times in his skits; ostensibly, he was the winner in the \"Best Insult Comic Dog\" category at Westminster 1997.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Dogs}}\n* [[AKC/Eukanuba National Championship]]\n* [[Crufts]]\n* [[List of Best in Show winners of the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show]]\n* [[World Dog Show]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Additional sources===\n*[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/histhighlights.html Westminster show history]\n*Barnes, Duncan (ed.) (1983). ''The AKC's World of the Pure-Bred Dog''. Nick Lyons Books. {{ISBN|0-87605-406-8}}.\n*Sifel, William F. (2001). ''The Dog Show: 125 Years of Westminster''. By William F. Stifel.  {{ISBN|0-9705698-0-7}}\n*Frei, David (ed.) (2010). ''The Westminster Kennel Club Guidebook''.  Latest edition of annual publication.\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikinewspar2|Four new breeds in the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show|'Banana Joe' wins Westminster}}\n* [http://www.msg.com/events/msg-dogs-page Official look behind the scenes at the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show]\n* [http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org Westminster Kennel Club official site]\n* [http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2004/02/0206_040206_westminster.html National Geographic news article about the show]\n* [http://blogs.msg.com/themonitor/2009/02/10/westminster-kennel-club-dog-show-dogs-get-glamorous-backstage/    Backstage at the 2009 Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/14/business/14kennel.html Hype, Money and Cornstarch: What It Takes to Win at Westminster]\n* [http://www.akc.org/events/titles.cfm List of American Kennel Club Titles and Abbreviations for Championship Dogs]\n\n{{Westminster Best in Show 07-70}}\n{{Westminster Best in Show}}\n\n[[Category:Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show| ]]\n[[Category:Dog shows and showing]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1877]]\n[[Category:American annual television specials]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Annual conformation show in New York City}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2007}}\n[[File:StumpWestminsterShow-wiki.jpg|thumb|Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show]]\nThe '''Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show''' is an all-breed [[conformation show]] that has been hosted in [[New York City]] annually since 1877. Currently, the breed and Junior Showmanship competitions are hosted at Piers 92 and 94, while the group and Best in Show competitions take place at [[Madison Square Garden]].\n\nThe Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show is one of a handful of [[Bench show|benched shows]] in the United States. Dogs are required to be on display in their assigned locations (show benches) during the entire show except when shown in the ring, groomed for showtime, or taken outside for elimination. This type of presentation allows spectators and breeders alike to have an opportunity of seeing all the entered dogs. (In the more common unbenched shows, dogs are required to be present only at assigned ring times.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.akc.org/expert-advice/sports/allan-unleashed-engaging-positively-public/|title=Engaging Positively With the Public at Dog Shows|first=Allan|last=Reznik|website=American Kennel Club|date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:WKC Dog Show Logo 2019.png|alt=A black-and-white stylized drawing of a hunting dog, nose poked out to the left of the image, tail erect and behind the dog, with a group of trees in the background.|thumb|The [[Westminster Kennel Club]] was formed in 1877.]]\nThe first Westminster show took place on May 8, 1877, making it second only to the [[Kentucky Derby]], in terms of continuously held sporting events in the United States. (Both events were held despite the [[Great Depression]] & [[World War]] years.) The show originated as a show for [[gun dog]]s, primarily [[Setter]]s and [[pointer (dog)|Pointers]], initiated by a group of hunters who met regularly at the Westminster Hotel at Irving Place and Sixteenth Street in [[Manhattan]]. They decided to create a [[kennel club]] called the Westminster Kennel Club specifically to hold a dog show. The prizes for these first shows included such items as pearl-handled pistols, which were of use to the hunters and terriermen who worked these dogs in the field.\n\n[[File:(King1893NYC) pg240 WESTMINISTER HOTEL, IRVING PLACE AND 16TH STREET.jpg|thumb|left|WESTMINISTER HOTEL, IRVING PLACE AND 16TH STREET]]\nHeld at Gilmore's Garden ([[Madison Square Garden (1879)|Madison Square Garden]]) the Westminster show drew over 1200 dogs. It proved so popular that it took four days instead of the three days originally scheduled. The club donated proceeds from the fourth day to the [[ASPCA]] for creation of a home for stray and disabled dogs.\n\nThe Westminster Kennel Club predates the formation of the [[American Kennel Club]] by seven years and became the first club admitted to the AKC after AKC's founding in 1884.  Breed parent clubs (e.g., the Collie  Club of America) create the standards for judging their breeds, with the AKC administering the rules about shows and judging.\n\nDogs are judged by how closely they conform to a written description of the ideal specimen of that breed (the breed standard). Many breeds no longer need to perform their original jobs and are bred mostly for companionship. However, they are still judged on their innate ability and physical makeup to perform their original jobs. Standards also include items that seem somewhat arbitrary such as color, eye shape, tail carriage and more.\n\nToday, Westminster takes place over two days and nights every February.  During the day, the dogs compete against other dogs of the same breed at Piers 92 and 94. Each Best of Breed winner (BOB) advances to the Group level. There are seven groups: Sporting, Hound, Working, Terrier, Toy, Non-Sporting, and Herding.  Group competition occurs during the evenings at Madison Square Garden. The seven Group winners advance to Best in Show, the final round of the show. During Best in Show, also held at Madison Square Garden, a judge will select one of judging othem as the Best In Show winner. Since 2014, the show allowed mixed-breed dogs to compete in an agility event.<ref>Jennifer Peltz, \"[https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/westminster-dog-show-adds-event-mixed-breeds-21547820 Westminster Dog Show Adds Event With Mixed Breeds],\" Associated Press, January 16, 2014.</ref>\n\nWestminster has held competitions in Junior Showmanship for handlers ages 9\u201318 since 1934. The eight finalists all receive scholarships for post-secondary schooling. The Club, through the Westminster Kennel Foundation also awards veterinary school scholarships for students from six schools yearly.\n\nThe winning dog becomes \"America's Dog\" for the comming year. Their reign begins with a media tour on the day following the show. They make appearances on nearly all television network morning shows, visit to the Observation Deck at the Empire State Building. The New York Stock Exchange also invites the winner to ring the opening bell.\n\nThe event is widely celebrated in New York City every February. The Empire State Building salutes the show by lighting its tower in the Westminster colors of purple and gold for the duration of the show. Saks 5th Avenue features a street window with a Westminster-themed display.\n\n==Controversy==\nAnimal-rights advocates such as [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] protest the show, arguing that the propagation and celebration of purebreds ultimately add to the millions of dogs who end up at and die in shelters.<ref>Jennifer Peltz, \"[https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/westminster-dog-show-adds-event-mixed-breeds-21547820 Westminster Dog Show Adds Event With Mixed Breeds,\"] Associated Press, 16 January 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.humanesociety.org/issues/pet_overpopulation/facts/pet_ownership_statistics.html Pets By the Numbers],\" Humane Society of the United States, September 27, 2013.</ref>\n\nAlso, during the 2019 broadcast, [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]] was reprimanded by dog show sponsor [[Ralston Purina|Purina]] after a broadcast voice-over introduction of a dog breed was done by [[NASCAR Cup Series]] champion [[Kyle Busch]], who is sponsored by a rival pet food maker, [[Mars Petcare]].\n\n==Announcers==\nFor many years, [[Roger A. Caras]] was known as \"the Voice of Westminster\" for providing the narration for the breed descriptions during the show.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/20/nyregion/roger-caras-72-animal-welfare-advocate.html | work=The New York Times | first=Sherri | last=Day | title=Roger Caras, 72, Animal Welfare Advocate | date=February 20, 2001}}</ref><ref>http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2012/02/11/v-print/2226292/pets-qa-best-in-show-really-means.html</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Michael J. LaFave was named show announcer at the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show.<ref>{{cite web|title=2004 Announcer|url=http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/2004/show/lafave.html|work=The Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show|publisher=Westminster Kennel Club|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref> He was replaced by Jim Fagan in 2010 but returned in 2011.<ref name=Ullmer>{{cite news|last=Ullmer|first=Mary|title=Unleashed: Unleash the hounds! Gentle giant Scottish deerhound is Westminster's Best in Show|url=http://www.mlive.com/living/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2011/02/unleashed_unleash_the_hounds_g.html|accessdate=May 24, 2012|newspaper=The Grand Rapids Press|date=February 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n[[CBS Sports]] covered the event from the late 1960s to the 1980s as part of its ''[[CBS Sports Spectacular]]'' anthology series.\n\nFrom 1984 until 2003, Universal's [[USA Network]] broadcast the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show. Following Universal's acquisition by General Electric in 2003 to form [[NBC Universal]], from 2004 until 2016, the show aired under the [[NBC Sports]] label. From 2006 through 2016, the Monday coverage was aired by business news channel [[CNBC]] due to conflicts with ''[[WWE Raw]]'' on the USA Network. On July 28, 2015, [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]] announced that it had acquired rights to the event under a 10-year deal beginning in 2017. For the first three years, [[Fox Sports 1]] and [[Nat Geo Wild]] provided joint coverage the show.\n\nDuring NBC's coverage from 1990 to 2016, [[David Frei]] co-hosted the event with partners, [[Al Trautwig]] (1990\u20131991,<ref>{{cite news|last=Dawson|first=Greg|title=USA's Westminster Dog Show a cult hit|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EYpJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DAwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5111,336923&dq|accessdate=May 24, 2012|newspaper=The News and Courier|date=February 16, 1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Zad|first=Martie|title=TNT features 'Kisses'|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-XlGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TOkMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3663,2494169&dq|accessdate=May 24, 2012|newspaper=The Daily Gazette|date=February 10, 1991}}</ref> 1993<ref>{{cite news|title=The dog days of February|newspaper=The Washington Times|date=February 13, 1993}}</ref>), [[Bud Collins]] (1992<ref>{{cite news|title=Bud Collins to Test Commentator Skills at National Dog Show|newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader|date=February 10, 1992}}</ref>), [[Joe Garagiola]] (1994\u20132002<ref>{{cite news|last=Dale|first=Steve|title=Canine Frenzy|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TvtPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ywgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6816,6119383&dq|accessdate=May 25, 2012|newspaper=Ocala Star-Banner|date=February 10, 2002}}</ref>), [[Mark McEwen]] (2003\u20132004<ref>{{cite web|last=Dale|first=Steve|title=The Voice of Westminster Dog Show|url=http://www.dogchannel.com/show/article_18009.aspx|work=Dog Channel.com|publisher=BowTie, Inc.|accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pennington|first=Gail|title=Critic's Picks|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=February 9, 2004}}</ref>), [[Lester Holt]] (2005, 2007\u20132008<ref>{{cite news|title=Westminster puts on the dogs|newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader|date=February 7, 2008}}</ref>), [[Debbye Turner]] (2006<ref>{{cite news|title=TV Digest|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=January 23, 2006}}</ref>), [[Mary Carillo]] (2009,<ref>{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=Former Westminster Winners Do Not Seem Past Their Prime|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/09/sports/othersports/09dogs.html|accessdate=May 25, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 8, 2009}}</ref> 2011<ref name=Ullmer />\u20132016), and [[Tamron Hall]] (2010<ref>{{cite web|title=USA Network & Westminster Brings Everyone's Best Friend Back to Madison Square Garden|url=http://newsblaze.com/story/2010012911590200001.pnw/topstory.html|work=News Blaze|accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref>).\n\nFrei provided the commentary of the 140th event for his final time. \n\nThe 141st event in 2017 marked the beginning of the [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]] contract. There are two sets of hosting teams.  From 2017\u201319, coverage aired on [[Fox Sports 1]] and [[National Geographic Wild]].  For 2017, daytime breed judging was hosted by [[Justin Kutcher]], Paula Nykiel and Jason Hoke and primetime coverage hosted by [[Chris Myers]] and Gail Miller Bisher.  In 2018, daytime bred judging was hosted by Kutcher, Kimberly Meredith Cavanna and Don Sturz in 2018, while Hoke joined the evening booth of Myers and Bisher. In 2019, the judging experts were swapped, with the day event hosted by Kutcher, Cavanna, and Hoke and evening event by Myers, Bisher, and Sturz.  <ref>{{cite web|title=Fox Sports Names Pick of the Litter for the 2017 Westminister Dog Show|url=http://www.foxsports.com/presspass/latestnews/2017/01/12/fox-sports-names-pick-of-the-litter-for-2017-westminster-dog-sho|website=Fox Sports Press Pass|publisher=Fox Sports public relations|date=January 12, 2017}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the acquisition of National Geographic TV Channels and the Fox TV Studios by the Walt Disney Company in 2019, event coverage in 2020 is limited solely to the two Fox Sports channels, Fox Sports 1 for primetime and [[Fox Sports 2]] for daytime judging.  [[John Strong (sportscaster)|John Strong]] replaced Kutcher as host for daytime breed judging and Fox hosts were Myers, Bisher, and Sturz.\n\nIn 2017, Fox Sports 1 aired a one-hour documentary, ''Crowned: Inside the Westminster Dog Show.''\n\n== Requirements for entry ==\n\nIn 1884, the AKC began requiring that all dog participants be registered with the AKC and recognized for conformation show competition. In 2016, there are 199 breeds and varieties eligible for Westminster. \nBecause of the show's popularity and prestige, starting in 1992 the AKC limited entries by requiring that dogs must have already earned their breed championship before appearing at Westminster. Later, the AKC amended that rule - dogs only need one of the two required \"major wins\" towards their championship titles. However, they don't need to be finished champions to enter.\n\nThe top five dogs in each breed (based on breed points earned in AKC conformation showing through October 31 of the preceding year), as well as the Best of Breed winner from each breed's national specialty show, receive printed invitations by mail and are eligible for early entry. After that entry deadline passes, other dogs with at least one \"major win\" may enter, up to a cut-off entry total of 2800 dogs.\n\nThere is no prohibition against a winner competing again in future Westminster shows. Seven dogs have won multiple Westminster championships: six dogs in consecutive years (including [[Warren Remedy]], the only three-time champion of the event) and one dog in non-consecutive years. Since 1972, however, there have been no repeat winners. (See [[List of Best in Show winners of the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show]].)\n\nDogs of all breeds, including [[mongrel|mutts]], may participate in the show's agility competition. There is a title for the highest-ranking mutt in the agility round - the \"All American Dog.\"\n\n== Winning breeds ==\n\nThrough the 134th Westminster Show (February 2010), [[Conformation show#Winning|Best in Show]] has been won by the [[Terrier]] group 45 out of the 103 times that the prize has been awarded since 1907,<ref>[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/bisrecords.html WestminsterKennelClub.org - ''Best In Show Awards By Breed (1907-2010)'']</ref> more than twice as many wins as any other group.  The single breed that has won the most is the Wire Fox Terrier, which has won 14 times. Two of the most popular dog breeds in the United States have never won Best in Show - they are the [[Labrador Retriever]] and the [[Golden Retriever]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akc.org/reg/dogreg_stats.cfm|title=The Labrador Retriever Wins Top Breed for the 26th Year In a Row|work=akc.org}}</ref>\n\n* [[Terrier]] group:  46\n* [[Gun dog|Sporting]] group: 18\n* [[Working dog|Working]] group: 15\n* [[Toy dog|Toy]] group: 11\n* Non-Sporting group: 10\n* [[Hound]] group: 6\n* [[Herding dog|Herding]] group: 3\n\nThe oldest dog to win Best in Show was a [[Sussex Spaniel]] named ''Ch. [[Clussexx Three D Grinchy Glee]]'' (a.k.a. Stump), at ten years of age in 2009. The youngest dog to win was a [[Rough Collie]] named ''Laund Loyalty of Bellhaven'', at nine months old in 1929.<ref>[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/bisrecords.html WestminsterKennelClub.org - ''Oldest Dogs To Win Best In Show'']</ref>  One dog, a [[Smooth Fox Terrier]] named ''Ch. Warren Remedy'' won Best in Show three times (1907\u20131909), and six other dogs have won twice.<ref>[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/bisrecords.html  WestminsterKennelClub.org - ''Multiple Best In Show Wins'']</ref>  Males have won Best in Show 68 times as opposed to females who have won 35 times.<ref>[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/bisrecords.html WestminsterKennelClub.org - ''Best In Show Awards By Sex Of The Dog'']</ref>\n\n===List of show winners and breeds===\n{{main|List of Best in Show winners of the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show}}\n\nFollowing is a list of ''WKC Best in Show'' winners since 1990.<ref>[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/biswinners.html Westminsterkennelclub.org - ''Best In Show Winners'']</ref>\n*2020: GCHP Stone Run Afternoon Tea - [[Poodle]]\n*2019: GCHB CH Kingarthur Van Foliny Home - [[Wire Fox Terrier]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/today/2019/02/king-a-wire-fox-terrier-crowned-best-in-show-at-the-2019-westminster-kennel-club-dog-show.html|title=King, a wire fox terrier, crowned best in show at the 2019 Westminster Kennel Club dog show|first1=Amy|last1=Kuperinsky||date=February 13, 2019|work=The Oregonian}}</ref>\n*2018: GCH Belle Creek's All I Care About Is Love - [[Bichon Frise]]\n*2017: Lockenhaus' Rumor Has It V Kenlyn - [[German Shepherd]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/14/sports/winner-westminster-dog-show-best-in-show.html|title=Westminster Dog Show 2017: Rumor the German Shepherd Wins Best in Show|first1=Kelly|last1=Whiteside|first2=Andrew|last2=Das|first3=Sarah|last3=Lyall|date=February 14, 2017|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n*2016: GCH Vjk-Myst Garbonita's California Journey (aka: ''\"CJ\"'') - [[Pointer (German Shorthaired)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2016/02/17/winning_dog_annoying_name.php|title=CJ The German Shorthaired Pointer Named 2016 Best In Show At Westminster Kennel Club's Big Night|last=Chung|first=Jen|website=Gothamist|access-date=October 11, 2016}}</ref>\n*2015: GCH ''[[Tashtins Lookin For Trouble]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Miss P\"'') - [[Beagle]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dogworld.co.uk/product.php/131233/1/canadians_triumph_at_westminster |title=Canadians triumph at Westminster |publisher=[[Dog World (newspaper)|Dog World]] |accessdate=February 18, 2015}}</ref>\n*2014: GCH ''Afterall Painting The Sky'' (a.k.a. ''\"Sky\"'') - [[Wire Fox Terrier]]<ref>http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/2014/results/bis/index.html</ref>\n*2013: GCH ''[[Banana Joe V Tani Kazari]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Banana Joe\"'') - [[Affenpinscher]]\n*2012: Ch. [[Palacegarden Malachy]] (a.k.a. ''\"Malachy\"'') - [[Pekingese]]\n*2011:  GCH ''[[Foxcliffe Hickory Wind]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Hickory\"'') - [[Scottish Deerhound]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://yourlife.usatoday.com/pets/pawprintpost/post/2011/02/westminster-best-in-show-winner/143180/1|title=Westminster Best in Show Winner: Scottish Deerhound|date=February 15, 2011|publisher=usatoday.com | accessdate=February 15, 2011| location=New York }}</ref>\n*2010:  Ch. ''[[Roundtown Mercedes of Maryscot]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Sadie\"'') - [[Scottish Terrier]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/house-and-home/sadie-crowned-top-dog-despite-interruption-1902148.html|title=Sadie crowned top dog despite interruption|date=February 17, 2010|work=The Independent|accessdate=February 17, 2010 | location=London | first=Oliver | last=Duff}}</ref>\n*2009:  Ch. ''[[Clussexx Three D Grinchy Glee]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Stump\"'') - [[Sussex Spaniel]]\n*2008:  Ch. ''[[K-Run's Park Me In First]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Uno''\" ) - [[Beagle]]\n*2007:  Ch. ''[[Felicity's Diamond Jim]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"James\"'' ) - [[English Springer Spaniel]]\n*2006:  Ch. ''Rocky Top's Sundance Kid'' (a.k.a. ''\"Rufus\"'' ) - [[Bull Terrier|Colored Bull Terrier]]\n*2005:  Ch. ''Kan-Point's VJK Autumn Roses'' (a.k.a. ''\"Carlee\"'' ) - [[German Shorthaired Pointer]]\n*2004:  Ch. ''Darbydale's All Rise Pouch Cove'' (a.k.a. ''\"Josh\"'' ) - [[Newfoundland (dog)|Newfoundland]]\n*2003:  Ch. ''[[Torums Scarf Michael]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Mick\"'' ) - [[Kerry Blue Terrier]]\n*2002:  Ch. ''Surrey Spice Girl'' (a.k.a. ''\"Spice\"'' ) - [[Miniature Poodle]]\n*2001:  Ch. ''Special Times Just Right'' (a.k.a. ''\"J.R.\"'' ) - [[Bichon Frise]]\n*2000:  Ch. ''Salilyn 'N Erin's Shameless'' (a.k.a. ''\"Samantha\"'' ) - [[English Springer Spaniel]]\n*1999:  Ch. ''[[Loteki Supernatural Being]]'' (a.k.a. ''\"Kirby\"'' ) - [[Papillon (dog)|Papillon]]\n*1998:  Ch. ''Fairewood Frolic'' (a.k.a. ''\"Rocki\"'' ) - [[Norwich Terrier]]\n*1997:  Ch. ''Parsifal Di Casa Netzer'' - [[Standard Schnauzer]]\n*1996:  Ch. ''Clussexx Country Sunrise'' (a.k.a. ''\"Brady\"'' ) - [[Clumber Spaniel]]\n*1995:  Ch. ''Gaelforce Post Script'' (a.k.a. ''\"Peggy Sue\"'' ) - Scottish Terrier\n*1994:  Ch. ''Chidley Willum The Conqueror'' - [[Norwich Terrier]]\n*1993:  Ch. ''Salilyn's Condor'' (a.k.a.: '\"Robert\"'' ) - [[English Springer Spaniel]]\n*1992:  Ch. ''Registry's Lonesome Dove'' (a.k.a. ''\"Lacey\"'' ) - [[Wire Fox Terrier]]\n*1991:  Ch. ''Whisperwind On A Carousel'' (a.k.a. ''\"Peter\"'' ) - [[Standard Poodle]]\n*1990:  Ch. ''Wendessa Crown Prince'' - [[Pekingese]]\n\n==Popular culture==\n* The 2000 comedy film ''[[Best in Show (film)|Best in Show]]'' takes place at the fictional \"Mayflower Kennel Club Dog Show,\" based in part on Westminster.\n*[[Triumph, the Insult Comic Dog]] has used the setting of the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show three times in his skits; ostensibly, he was the winner in the \"Best Insult Comic Dog\" category at Westminster 1997.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Dogs}}\n* [[AKC/Eukanuba National Championship]]\n* [[Crufts]]\n* [[List of Best in Show winners of the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show]]\n* [[World Dog Show]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Additional sources===\n*[http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org/history/histhighlights.html Westminster show history]\n*Barnes, Duncan (ed.) (1983). ''The AKC's World of the Pure-Bred Dog''. Nick Lyons Books. {{ISBN|0-87605-406-8}}.\n*Sifel, William F. (2001). ''The Dog Show: 125 Years of Westminster''. By William F. Stifel.  {{ISBN|0-9705698-0-7}}\n*Frei, David (ed.) (2010). ''The Westminster Kennel Club Guidebook''.  Latest edition of annual publication.\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikinewspar2|Four new breeds in the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show|'Banana Joe' wins Westminster}}\n* [http://www.msg.com/events/msg-dogs-page Official look behind the scenes at the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show]\n* [http://www.westminsterkennelclub.org Westminster Kennel Club official site]\n* [http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2004/02/0206_040206_westminster.html National Geographic news article about the show]\n* [http://blogs.msg.com/themonitor/2009/02/10/westminster-kennel-club-dog-show-dogs-get-glamorous-backstage/    Backstage at the 2009 Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/14/business/14kennel.html Hype, Money and Cornstarch: What It Takes to Win at Westminster]\n* [http://www.akc.org/events/titles.cfm List of American Kennel Club Titles and Abbreviations for Championship Dogs]\n\n{{Westminster Best in Show 07-70}}\n{{Westminster Best in Show}}\n\n[[Category:Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show| ]]\n[[Category:Dog shows and showing]]\n[[Category:Recurring events 