{"title_page": "Kiddle (search engine)", "text_new": "{{short description|Search engine and online encyclopedia emphasizing safety for children}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = Kiddle\n| logo = [[File:Kids-search-engine-i.png|220px|Kiddle]]\n| screenshot = Kiddle-homepage.png\n| screenshot_size = 300px\n| caption = Kiddle's desktop home page\n| url = {{URL|https://www.kiddle.co }}\n| type = [[Search engine]]\n| language = English\n| registration = No\n| launch_date = 2014\n| alexa = {{increase}} 15,589 (Global, April 2020)\n}}\n'''Kiddle.co''' is a [[web search engine]] and [[online encyclopedia]] emphasizing safety for young children. Kiddle is powered by [[Google Custom Search]] and employs [[SafeSearch]], with additional filters. The user enters topics in the search toolbar, and Kiddle returns and ranks its findings, and pushes child-safe content higher in its search results.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Kiddle-logo.png|thumb|190x190px|Kiddle's logo in 2014]]\nKiddle's domain was registered in 2014. The designers chose the [[.co]] domain name  to emphasize that Kiddle is a quality \"child-safe\" search engine.<ref name=\"about\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiddle.co/about.php|title=About Kiddle - visual search engine for kids|website=www.kiddle.co|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> Kiddle became very popular in social media in 2016, and even became a meme due to blocking of certain words for a short period of time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/opinion/2016/03/01/child-friendly-search-engine-kiddle-is-promoting-ignorance-not-safety/|title='Child-friendly' search engine Kiddle is promoting ignorance|last=Connolly|first=Amanda|date=2016-03-01|website=The Next Web|language=en-us|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref> \n\n== Format ==\nKiddle uses an outer space stylized theme for their pages.<ref name=\"tech times\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.techtimes.com/articles/136639/20160225/kiddle-search-engine-kids.htm|title=Kiddle Search Engine Is The Google For Kids|last=Keating|first=Lauren|date=2016-02-25|website=Tech Times|language=en|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref>  It appears like a [[Google Custom Search]] window. After the user enters the subject, Kiddle presents search results, with the first three results being deemed safe and written specifically for kids and \"checked by Kiddle editors\", the next four being safe sites not written specially for kids, but presented in kid friendly language. The eighth result and anything else beyond are safe sites written for adults but harder to understand for kids. Results presented are filtered through Google [[SafeSearch]].<ref name=\"tech times\"/><ref name=\"about\"/> \n\nIf the user enters what are considered \"bad words\" a picture of a robot is displayed, telling the user to try again.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-35694883|title='Safe' search engine blocks common words|first=Zoe|last=Kleinman|date=1 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=23 January 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n== Kpedia ==\n'''Kiddle Encyclopedia''' ('''Kpedia''') is an online encyclopedia, available from their search engine, powered by [[MediaWiki]]. It lists over 700,000 articles, and is \"based on selected content and facts from Wikipedia, rewritten for children.\" Kiddle positions its Kpedia as an educational resource to be used for \"school homework help and general education,\" and includes their articles in search results.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kids.kiddle.co/|title=Kids encyclopedia facts|author=|date=|website=kids.kiddle.co|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.komando.com/tips/529215/7-search-sites-to-use-other-than-google|title=7 search sites to use other than Google|last=Navarro|first=Francis|last2=Kom|website=The Kim Komando Show|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-21|last3=o.com}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nIn 2016, Kiddle was criticized for blocking the keywords \"gay,\" \"lesbian,\" and the phrase \"sex education,\" claiming that the keywords were not suitable for small children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-35694883|title='Safe' search engine blocks common words|last=Kleinman|first=Zoe|work=BBC News|date=2016-03-01|access-date=2019-01-21|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/opinion/2016/03/01/child-friendly-search-engine-kiddle-is-promoting-ignorance-not-safety/|title='Child-friendly' search engine Kiddle is promoting ignorance|last=Connolly|first=Amanda|date=2016-03-01|website=[[The Next Web]]|language=en-us|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref> They had also banned the words \"transgender\", and \"bisexual\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/kiddle-child-friendly-google-search-site-bans-words-including-bisexual-and-transgender-a6903551.html|title=The 'child-friendly Google' bans swearwords like bisexual and transgender|last=Griffin|first=Andrew|date=2016-02-29|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref> Due to public outcry, Kiddle announced they would unblock these words.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pix11.com/2016/03/05/kid-friendly-search-engine-kiddle-unblocks-inappropriate-words-after-backlash/|title=Kid-friendly search engine Kiddle unblocks \u2018inappropriate\u2019 words after backlash|author=|date=5 March 2016|website=pix11.com|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nKiddle is powered by Google Custom Search but is not affiliated with [[Google|Google LLC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiddle.co/about.php|title=About Kiddle - visual search engine for kids|website=www.kiddle.co|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> However, it has been mistaken for a Google product in several news articles and blogs due to its name<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nakedsecurity.sophos.com/2019/03/19/child-friendly-search-engines-how-safe-is-kiddle/|title=Child-friendly search engines: How safe is Kiddle?|date=2019-03-19|website=Naked Security|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>. \n\n== See also ==\n* [[KidRex]]\n* [[KidzSearch]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal |last=Shields |first=Jane |date=Winter 2016 |title=Virtual Toolkit |type=Product Review |journal=[[Screen Education]] |issue=82 |pages=102\u2013104}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ivers |first=Karen S. |title=Using Technology to Support High-Impact Educational Practice |publisher=Libraries Unlimited |year=2018 |pages=131}}\n* {{cite book |last=Peachey |first=Nik |title=Thinking Critically through Digital Media |publisher=PeacheyPublications Ltd |year=2016 |pages=160}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hertz |first=Mary Beth |title=Digital and Media Literacy in the Age of the Internet: Practical Classroom Applications |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2019 |pages=64,205}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.kiddle.co}}\n{{Web search engines}}\n\n[[Category:Internet search engines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Search engine and online encyclopedia emphasizing safety for children}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = Kiddle\n| logo = [[File:Kids-search-engine-i.png|220px|Kiddle]]\n| screenshot = Kiddle-homepage.png\n| screenshot_size = 300px\n| caption = Kiddle's desktop home page\n| url = {{URL|https://www.kiddle.co }}\n| type = [[Search engine]]\n| language = English\n| registration = No\n| launch_date = 2014\n| alexa = {{increase}} 15,589 (Global, April 2020)\n}}\n'''Kiddle.co''' is a [[web search engine]] and [[online encyclopedia]] emphasizing safety for young children. Kiddle is powered by [[Google Custom Search]] and employs [[SafeSearch]], with additional filters. The user enters topics in the search toolbar, and Kiddle returns and ranks its findings, and pushes child-safe content higher in its search results.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Kiddle-logo.png|thumb|190x190px|Kiddle's logo in 2014]]\nKiddle's domain was registered in 2014. The designers chose the [[.co]] domain name  to emphasize that Kiddle is a quality \"child-safe\" search engine.<ref name=