[MediaWiki]]. It lists over 700,000 articles, and is \"based on selected content and facts from Wikipedia, rewritten for children.\" Kiddle positions its Kpedia as an educational resource to be used for \"school homework help and general education,\" and includes their articles in search results.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kids.kiddle.co/|title=Kids encyclopedia facts|author=|date=|website=kids.kiddle.co|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.komando.com/tips/529215/7-search-sites-to-use-other-than-google|title=7 search sites to use other than Google|last=Navarro|first=Francis|last2=Kom|website=The Kim Komando Show|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-21|last3=o.com}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nIn 2016, Kiddle was criticized for blocking the keywords \"gay,\" \"lesbian,\" and the phrase \"sex education,\" claiming that the keywords were not suitable for small childern.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-35694883|title='Safe' search engine blocks common words|last=Kleinman|first=Zoe|work=BBC News|date=2016-03-01|access-date=2019-01-21|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/opinion/2016/03/01/child-friendly-search-engine-kiddle-is-promoting-ignorance-not-safety/|title='Child-friendly' search engine Kiddle is promoting ignorance|last=Connolly|first=Amanda|date=2016-03-01|website=[[The Next Web]]|language=en-us|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref> They had also banned the words \"transgender\", and \"bisexual\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/kiddle-child-friendly-google-search-site-bans-words-including-bisexual-and-transgender-a6903551.html|title=The 'child-friendly Google' bans swearwords like bisexual and transgender|last=Griffin|first=Andrew|date=2016-02-29|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref> Due to public outcry, Kiddle announced they would unblock these words.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pix11.com/2016/03/05/kid-friendly-search-engine-kiddle-unblocks-inappropriate-words-after-backlash/|title=Kid-friendly search engine Kiddle unblocks \u2018inappropriate\u2019 words after backlash|author=|date=5 March 2016|website=pix11.com|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nKiddle is powered by Google Custom Search but is not affiliated with [[Google|Google LLC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiddle.co/about.php|title=About Kiddle - visual search engine for kids|website=www.kiddle.co|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> However, it has been mistaken for a Google product in several news articles and blogs due to its name<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nakedsecurity.sophos.com/2019/03/19/child-friendly-search-engines-how-safe-is-kiddle/|title=Child-friendly search engines: How safe is Kiddle?|date=2019-03-19|website=Naked Security|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>. \n\n== See also ==\n* [[KidRex]]\n* [[KidzSearch]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal |last=Shields |first=Jane |date=Winter 2016 |title=Virtual Toolkit |type=Product Review |journal=[[Screen Education]] |issue=82 |pages=102\u2013104}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ivers |first=Karen S. |title=Using Technology to Support High-Impact Educational Practice |publisher=Libraries Unlimited |year=2018 |pages=131}}\n* {{cite book |last=Peachey |first=Nik |title=Thinking Critically through Digital Media |publisher=PeacheyPublications Ltd |year=2016 |pages=160}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hertz |first=Mary Beth |title=Digital and Media Literacy in the Age of the Internet: Practical Classroom Applications |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2019 |pages=64,205}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.kiddle.co}}\n{{Web search engines}}\n\n[[Category:Internet search engines]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCriticism:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: childern \u2192 children", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kiddle_(search_engine)"}
